			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2019</a> paper:</span><br><i>Spectrum-based fault localization for context-free grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MoeketsiRaselimo.html">Moeketsi Raselimo</a>, <a href="../profile/BerndFischer.html">Bernd Fischer</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3357766.3359538">10.1145/3357766.3359538</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2024s/paper08.html"><em>Spectrum-based rule- and item-level localization of faults in context-free grammars</em></a> (SLE 2024 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> The paper primarily contributes techniques for language definition (often syntax-related) as part of language design.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It uses compilation/generation/refinement to derive executable artifacts (vertical transformations).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL">T6B: Industrial</span></a><ul><li> It is motivated by or evaluated in an industrial/practical context.
</li></ul></li></ul>
